<section class="primary">

# Functions

Let $f$ be a function defined on some interval $(a, \infty)$. Then $$ \xlimit{x}{\infty}\;f(x) = L $$ means
that for every $\epsilon > 0$ there is a corresponding number $N$ such that if $x > N$ then $|\;f(x)-L| < \epsilon$.
We say this function **converges**. 

Similarly, $$ \xlimit{x}{\infty}\;f(x)=\infty $$ means that for every positive number $M$ there is a corresponding 
positive number $N$ such that if $x > N$ then $f(x) > M$. We say this function **diverges**.

</section>

<section class="primary">

# Sequences and Series

There are many types of sequences and series, and their convergence (or lack thereof) can be determined in a variety of
ways. For example, given a geometric sequence, we can determine its convergence by the ratio being exponentiated. More
precisely:

The sequence $\{r^n\}$ is convergent if $-1 < r \leq 1$ and divergent for all other values of $r$:
$$
  \xlimit{n}{\infty} r^n = \begin{cases}
    0 &\text{ if } -1 < r < 1 \\
    1 &\text{ if } r = 1
  \end{cases}
$$

Other sequence and series convergence/divergence concepts are discussed under [series](series).

